More About The Linux Command Line

6 steps

In this short tutorial, you will learn more on the basics of some of the most commonly known commands on the Linux command line such as getting system information, listing directories, translating text (in terms of position), replacing text in files in place, and finding files with different options and settings.

You do not need to learn everything about them but just enough to be able to navigate and modify files and directories smoothly around the command line.

For technical help on the StackUp platform, join our Discord and ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Required to have a Linux operating system such as Ubuntu or WSL. MacOS users do not require the need to run a Linux operating system as both have similar shell environments. However, if you encounter some issues, please report to our Discord server!

Important: Some commands can modify files and directories in your filesystem. A mistake can lead to loss of data. We require you to use a cloud environment instead!

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Get your system's information
  • Manage files and directories effectively
  • Navigate and find files effectively
  • Run commands with find

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Preparing Your Environment

    For those who prefer to use a Linux environment but do not have a machine to install a Linux operating system, you can create a GitHub Codespace environment instead. This requires you to have an existing GitHub account, otherwise, you must first create a new GitHub account.

    Once logged in, head to https://github.com/github/codespaces-blank and create a GitHub Codespace.

    Once inside your codespace, let's try out some commands. Run the following command.

    uname -a

    This gives you quick system information such as the architecture used, the kernel version, and the current date. Depending on the environment, your output may vary. For example, a bare metal installation of a Linux operating system will give a different output as compared to those from GitHub Codespace.

    Care to share yours? Just head to our Discord server and share your output!
    -

    This command, as mentioned before, gives basic system information. It helps identify what operating system you are using and what kind of Linux distribution (if you are using Linux) as different distributions might have different system configurations.

    Information is valuable in many areas such as reporting bugs, identifying incompatibilities, and knowing if the version of the operating system is vulnerable to security issues.

  • Step 2: inxi

    Aside from the uname command, there is also the inxi command. Although, this command may not be guaranteed to be installed so you have to install it manually in your operating system. For example, to install it on Ubuntu, you have to run the following commands.

    sudo apt update -y
sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install inxi -y

    inxi provides more information with clear labels such as memory, available storage space, and it may also include which devices, and firmware are currently running or available in the system.

    Assuming you have successfully installed inxi, run the following command.

    inxi

    inxi also has other flags as well that are good information such as location of the machine, battery, bluetooth devices, and graphics card information. It even gives information about the weather, although that requires a network connection.

    For example, the command for getting the weather, graphics card, and basic information, run the following command

    inxi -wbG

    Some info might be hidden as shown by the above screenshot and require admin privileges. To get the hidden information, run the following command.

    sudo inxi -wbG

    Here is a sample screenshot of the command with admin privileges.

    inxi has multiple flags to try out. To get all the available flags, just run the following command.

    inxi -h

    Try out all the available flags.

  • Step 3: Echo, Appending, Tee, Cat and Other Very Useful Commands

    Let's create a bunch of files and directories. First let's create a test directory. Run the following command.

    mkdir -p test_directory

    Head into test_directory. Then run the following command.

    for i in {1..30};
do
  echo $i > file$i
done

    This shell script will create 30 files with a filename that follows this format: file<number>.

    You can check that you have created 30 files by running the following command.

    ls

    The output should be similar to the screenshot below.

    Each file's content is a number the same number associated with the same file e.g. file1 has a text 1 as its content.

    Run the following command.

    echo "Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit" >> file22

    What does this do? This command redirects and appends the text "Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit" without the double quotes into the file file22 in the next line. The contents of file22 should look like the one below.

    22
Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit
    Plain text

    What happens if we do the following commands instead?

    cat file22 >> file1
cat file22 > file2

    The first cat command outputs the content of file22 and the operator >> appends it to file1. The second cat command outputs the content of file22 and the operator > replaces whatever is in the content of file2. Therefore, file1 now has the following contents.

    1
22
Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit
    Plain text

    Whereas, file2 now has the following contents.

    22
Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit
    Plain text

    Since the second cat command replaces the content of file2 with file22, that also means that both files are considered the same. You can check this by getting the hashes of both files by running the command below.

    sha256sum file22 file2

    It should have a similar output like the text below.

    897943de43ec3f70b55373ac8d086c4c1e651bb708758983c98e5e4c07cd5f8c  file22
897943de43ec3f70b55373ac8d086c4c1e651bb708758983c98e5e4c07cd5f8c  file2

    Sometimes, you just want to output the text while also input the text into a file. You can use the tee command with this. Run the following command below.

    cat file1 | tee file100

    You can see that you get an output of the contents of file1 while also inputting the same content into a new file called file100.

    tee also has an append option by adding a -a flag. Run the following command below.

    cat file1 | tee -a file20

    file20 now contains the following text.

    20
1
22
Neque porro quisquam est qui dolorem ipsum quia dolor sit amet, consectetur, adipisci velit
    Plain text

    For a quick recap, here are the things you should know after trying out those commands:

    • The symbol | is called a pipe operator and it redirects standard output (or standard error if a command errors) to another command. It allows you to chain multiple commands as needed.
    • The symbols > and >> are called "redirection" operators. The first variant redirects the output to a file, regardless, if the file already has contents or not. This means, it will replace all contents of a file if such a file already exists. The second variant redirects AND appends the output of the command, regardless, if the file already has contents or not.
    • The sha256sum command outputs the hashes of a file or files. Other variants exist to get a hash of a file such as md5sum, sha1sum, and sha512sum.
    • The cat command or concatenate command has many uses such as editing files, and to concatenate several files into one output e.g. cat file1 file2 > file200 will concatenate the contents of file1 and file2 first as output. Editing files, however, is quite limited, hence, it won't be covered in this tutorial.
    • The tee command reads from standard input and writes content to standard output and files.
  • Step 4: Searching, Modifying Text and Counting Lines

    Ensure that you are still inside the test_directory directory before running the following command.

    grep ipsum file1

    This should output text on your terminal with the text "ipsum" highlighted in a different colour e.g. in red colour.

    The grep command helps find patterns in files. You can use regex patterns too such as using the | operator with the -E flag.

    grep -E "qui|dolo" file1

    You can also search patterns in multiple files as well.

    grep -E "qui|dolo" file1 file100

    To search all files within a directory, run the following command.

    grep -E "qui|dolo" file1 file100

    You can also add what line numbers are the matching patterns by adding the -n flag.

    grep -En "qui|dolo" ./*

    Let's try to modify text output (without modifying the files yet). Run the following command.

    cat file1 file2 | cut -d' ' -f12

    The cut command cuts the text output at every whitespace character and outputs the text at the 12th column. You can also change the delimiter to another character other than a whitespace e.g. "d".

    cat file1 file2 | cut -d'd' -f4

    Run the following command.

    cat file1 file2 | tr qui woo

    The tr command replaces any instance of the text "qui" to "woo" but it does not replace existing non-whitespace characters if the replacement text is too long.

    Run the following command.

    cat file1 file2 | tr '[:lower:]' '[:upper:]'

    The tr command changes any lowercase characters to uppercase characters. The reverse can also be done by just changing the order like the following command.

    cat file1 file2 | tr '[:lower:]' '[:upper:]' | tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]'

    There is also another command that allows you to have more control in modifying text. Run the following command.

    sed 's/qui/stackup/g' file1

    The sed command should replace "qui" with the text "stackup" while preserving the positions of other text unlike the tr command.

    You can also do an in-place modification with sed. This means that not only does it output a modified form of the text, it also modifies the contents of the file as well with the output text. Run the following commands.

    sed -i 's/qui/stackup/g' file1
cat file1

    By now, you can see that the contents of file1 changed in-place.

    Again, we won't cover every possible option of all the mentioned commands. At the end of the tutorial, you will know where to get documentation about these commands. You will also get a good command line tool that will help you get a summary of how to use these commands.

  • Step 5: Finding Files

    One of the most helpful commands on Linux is the find command. Like its name, it helps find files and directories with different options and settings.

    Inside the test_directory, run the following commands.

    mkdir -p stackup/learn/and/earn
mkdir -p earn/and/learn/at/stackup
touch stackup/{1,2,3,4,5}
touch earn/and/{foo,fie,fow,boom}
touch earn/and/learn/at/{foo,fie,fow,boom}

    Run the following command.

    tree

    This should give you an output text that lists all your files and directories in a tree-like structure.

    find . -type f

    This should output the following.

    You can also just list the directories.

    find . -type d

    You can also specify the name of the file or directory. Run the following commands.

    find . -type f -name boom
find . -type d -name at

    Let's create more files. Run the following commands.

    touch stackup/{1,2,3,4,5,6}.rs
touch earn/and/learn/{1,2,3,4,5,6}.py
touch earn/and/{1,2,3,4,5,6}.txt

    This should create the files in those intended directories with the file extensions ".rs", ".py", and ".txt".

    Run the following commands to check if those with file extensions exist.

    find . -type f -name "*.rs"
find . -type f -name "*.py"
find . -type f -name "*.txt"

    Yours should output similar to the screenshot below.

    Another cool thing to do with find is to run commands on files or directories that match. Be careful as the following command will remove files.

    find . -type f -name "*.txt" -exec rm -v {} \;

    Run the following command.

    find . -type f -name "*.txt"

    This should give you a blank output. This means those files with the ".txt" file extension were removed with the rm command.

    Amazing! With find, you can find files or directories with a specified name, you can find files based on file extensions and you can also execute shell commands on those files or directories!

  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations! You have finished this tutorial. You have learned more about the Linux command line. However, those are only a fraction of what all those commands can do! You can find those in the following links.

    • https://manpages.ubuntu.com/
    • https://man.archlinux.org/

    For example, to get more information about the find command, you can search it on the links above.

    These documentations are called manpages. Short for manual pages, they are the built-in documentation for commands, programs, system calls, and configuration files in Unix-like operating systems, including Linux. They provide detailed information about a particular command, its options, usage, and sometimes examples. Manpages are an essential part of the command-line interface in Linux.

    For example, a web version of the manpage for find is at this link.

    Manpages also exist on the command line too by just running the man command. For example, to get to know more about the cat command, run the following command.

    man cat

    Your terminal output will look similar to the screenshot below.

    Go try out searching every possible option of other commands and try them out!

    But, it does get a little tedious to read manpages, so here is the command line tool that can help you out, the tldr command line tool. There is also a Rust variant of tldr.

    If you have other questions and suggestions in improving this tutorial, feel free to send your feedback in our Discord server!
